Post-vent vasculature which forms an interconnecting network of venous tubes. The caudal vein plexus forms via a very active period of angiogenic sprouting, beginning at 25 hpf when venous endothelial cells of the posterior cardinal vein sprout and migrate ventrally, then fuse with neighboring tip cells. This process reiterates during a five-hour window, forming a primordial plexus by 30 hpf. By two days of development, the primitive caudal vein plexus has matured into a complex, well-perfused, venous vascular network. Starting at 4 dpf the caudal vein plexus starts to remodel and simplify.
Dense regular connective tissue that connects muscle to bone.

Blood vessels that connect the dorsal aorta or the posterior cardinal vein and the dorsal longitudinal anastomotic vessel. They run along the vertical myotomal boundaries.  At early stages these vessels don't have venous or arterial markers.
Groove that is in the ventral optic cup and through which blood vessels pass to the enclosed mesenchyme.
Anatomical space that is located in the center of the iris and allows light to impinge on the retina.
Joint that articulates the mesethmoid and vomer. Mesethmoid-vomer joint is unpaired.

The anterior lobe of the hypophysis (pituitary gland). This lobe contains cells that produce prolactin, growth hormone, thyroid-stimulating hormone, follicle-stimulating hormone and proopiomelanocortin. In contrast to mammalian vertebrates, the adenohypophysis remains in a subepithelial position and there exists no equivalent of Rathke's pouch in zebrafish.

comments: Changed start to long-pec from protruding mouth. In future, make a primordium and split the stages.

definition.val: Branchiostegal ray 2 is between rays 1 and 3 and ossifies second.
Ligament that run from the dorsal tip of the cleithrum to the exoccipital.
Ligament that connects the  rostral process of the maxilla  to the kinethmoid.
Ligament that connects the dentary to the maxilla.
The ligament that connects the anteroventral tips of ceratobranchials 5 medially.
Proliferative region at the periphery of the retina where retinal stem cells are located. After 60 hpf, the CMZ is the source of most retinal growth.
Ligament that, in the adult, attaches the premaxilla to its counterpart at the midline and the kinethmoid posterodorsally.
The anterior compartment of the swim bladder is thought to have acoustic resonance properties that play a key role in audition.  It is connected to the posterior chamber via the ductus communicans.

Odontoid tissue formed of a loose matrix of collagen.  The fibrils of the predentine are homogeneously distributed and preferentially oriented along the long axis of the tooth. They are of variable thickness, measuring from 50 to 100 nm in diameter.
Joint that articulates segments of the fin ray.
Ligament that connects one rib to another.
Ligament that connects the intercalarium to the  anterior process of the tripus and the scaphium.

The coronomeckelian is a membrane bone that ossifies on Meckel's cartilage where the tendon from the adductor mandibulae A3 inserts (6.1mm).  In the adult, the coronomeckelian is a small, irregularly shaped bone that is fused to the dorsomedial surface of the anguloarticular, just dorsal to Meckel's cartilage.
Ligament that runs from the ventral third of the supracleithrum to the exoccipital.
The ventral portion of the first pharyngeal arch, comprising the lower jaw.
The dorsal portion of the first pharyngeal arch, comprising the upper jaw.
Ligaments that runs from the parapophyses of the anteriormost centrum to the exoccipital.  There are two  scapulo-vertebral ligaments in zebrafish.
A regenerating tissue composed of a proliferative mass of undifferentiated progenitor cells from which new differentiated structures arise.
Fibrous joint that articulates the posterior edge of the  preopercle horizontal limb with the symplectic.
Fossa on the pterotic  where the hyomandibula articulates.
Skeletal element which is part of lepidotrichium articulating with other lepidotrichium segments by lepidotrichium joints.
Branchiostegal ray that is the most anterior ray which ossifies last (5.5 mm NL).

The posterior compartment of the swim bladder plays a key role in buoyancy control.  It is connected to the anterior chamber via the ductus communicans.  This chamber corresponds to the swim bladder found in larval fish.
Fibrous joint that articulates the anterior edge of the preopercle vertical limb and the  hyomandibula.
Stage III follicles (340-690 microns) contain a stage 3 oocyte.
Skeletal element that forms as a replacement or substitution of another element or tissue.
Stage II follicles (140-340 microns) contain a stage 2 oocyte.
Skeletal tissue that is part of the exoskeleton and derived from an odontogenic papilla.
Stage IV follicles (690-730 microns) contain a stage 4 oocyte and are considered mature.
Synovial joint that articulates the hyomandibula and the opercle.
Stage I follicles (less than 140 microns) contain a stage 1 oocyte and are in the primary growth stage.
Space enclosed by the trabeculae cranii.  The anterior tip of the notochord extends into the posterior region of the hypophyseal fenestra.
Fossa where the exoccipital forms the medial portion and the epioccipital forms the lateral margin.
Portion of tissue that gives rise to the immature gonad.
Synovial joint that articulates the hyomandibula with the pterotic.

The zebrafish endocrine pancreas is an compound organ component composed of small groups of islet cells that are distributed throughout the exocrine pancreas.  The islet cells produce insulin, glucagon and somatostatin.

comments: May be called pancreatic islets of Langerhans (related synonym). Alpha cells secrete glucagon like peptide, beta-insulin, delta cells-somatostatin, pancreastatin.  May also be called "Brockman bodies".

definition.val: Foramen in the hyomandibula that allows passage of the anterior lateral line nerve and the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII). The foramen develop in the hyosymplectic.  The hyomandibular foramen are paired.
A skeletal element that has the potential to participate in endochondral ossification, and may participate in intramembranous ossification.
Fin undergoing the process of regeneration.
Skeletal tissue that is avascular, rich in glycosaminoglycans (GAGs) and typically includes chondrocytes within isolated lacunae. Cartilage tissue is deposited by chondroblasts.
Is a duct part of the testis that carries sperm and fluid to the cloaca.
Is an interconnected tubular multi-tissue structure that contains fluid that is actively transported around the head.

Skeletal tissue with a collagen-rich extracellular matrix vascularized, mineralized with hydroxyapatite and typically including osteocytes located in lacunae that communicate with one another by cell processes (in canaliculi). Bone is deposited by osteoblasts.
Fibrous joint connecting the supraoccipital to the parietal bone.
Synchondrosis where the basioccipital meets the prootic anteriorly.
Synostosis where the ectopterygoid meets the entopterygoid.
Opening formed between the ventral border of the metapterygoid and the dorsal border of the symplectic.
Synostosis where the entopterygoid meets the metapterygoid. The metapterygoid has an anterodorsally projecting spine that meets the entopterygoid medially in a synostosis at its posteromedial edge.
Pharyngobranchial bone of the fifth pharyngeal arch that lies approximately posteromedial to epibranchial 2 and medial to epibranchial 3.
Synostosis where anteromedial extensions of the lateral ethmoid project to meet the supraethmoid dorsally.
Pharyngobranchial cartilage which forms in close proximity to or fused with pharyngobranchial 3; may not be distinguishable as a separate element in the adult. Remains cartilaginous.
Synchondrosis where the quadrate meets the entopterygoid dorsally.

Pharyngobranchial 2 (misidentified as pharyngobranchial 1 in Cubbage & Mabee, 1993 and Mayden 1989) is present and separate from pharyngobranchial 3.  It (8.0 mm) ossifies after pharyngobranchial 3. In the adult, the cartilaginous anterior end of the ossified pharyngobranchial 2 articulates with the cartilaginous medial tip of epibranchial 1. It articulates anterolaterally and posterolaterally with the anterior and posterior cartilaginous tips of epibranchial2.  In Cyprinidae pb3 overlaps pb2 (Siebert, 1987; Cavender & Coburn, 1992) but does not fuse to it.
Connective tissue that functions in mechanical and structural support.
Cartilaginous joint that articulates the anguloarticular posteroventrally with the retroarticular.
Floor plate that is part of the rhombomeres.
Portion of tissue that is the medial part of the floor plate and is located adjacent to the notochord.
Synostosis where the entopterygoid meets the quadrate.
Joint in which the articulating bones are connected by bone.
Portion of tissue that is the lateral part of the floor plate.

A cellular receptor which mediates the sense of temperature. Thermoreceptors in vertebrates are mostly located under the skin. In mammals there are separate types of thermoreceptors for cold and for warmth and pain receptor cells which detect cold or heat extreme enough to cause pain.

A mechanoreceptor cell located in the inner ear that is sensitive to auditory stimuli. The accessory sensory structures are arranged so that appropriate stimuli cause movement of the hair-like projections (stereocilia and kinocilia) which relay the information centrally in the nervous system.

comments: Has alt_id CL:0000201.

definition.val: A cell specialized to transduce mechanical stimuli and relay that information centrally in the nervous system.
Muscle pioneer cell part of somite 19.
Muscle pioneer cell part of somite 16.
Muscle pioneer cell part of somite 13.
Muscle pioneer cell part of somite 10.
A cell specialized to detect and transduce light.
Muscle pioneer cell part of somite 6.
Muscle pioneer cell part of somite 30.

A cell specialized to detect chemical substances and relay that information centrally in the nervous system. Chemoreceptors may monitor external stimuli, as in taste and olfaction, or internal stimuli, such as the concentrations of oxygen and carbon dioxide in the blood.
Muscle pioneer cell part of somite 28.
Muscle pioneer cell part of somite 25.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 18.
A cell that takes up and metabolizes substances.
Muscle pioneer cell part of somite 22.
A cell whose function is determined by the generation or the reception of an electric signal.

An elongated, contractile cell found wrapped about precapillary arterioles outside the basement membrane. Pericytes are present in capillaries where proper adventitial and muscle layer are missing (thus distinguishing this cell type from adventitial cells). They are relatively undifferentiated and may become fibroblasts, macrophages, or smooth muscle cells.

comments: CL:0000184 was merged into CL:0000699.

definition.val: The main structural component of the liver. They are specialized epithelial cells that are organized into interconnected plates called lobules.
Multi-tissue structure forming the sides of the lumen of the neural tube in rhombomere 4.
Multi-tissue structure forming the sides of the lumen of the neural tube in rhombomere 1.
Multi-tissue structure forming the sides of the lumen of the diencephalic region of the neural tube.
A muscle cell that is small, darkly colored, with high lipid and mitochondrial content.
Mesoderm that is part of the pectoral fin bud.
Mesenchyme part of dorsal fin.
A mature contractile cell, commonly known as a myocyte, that forms one of three kinds of muscle.

nodes.lbl: mesenchyme derived from head neural crest

definition.val: Multi-tissue structure forming the sides of the lumen of the telencephalic region of the neural tube.
The peripheral receptor for pain. Includes receptors which are sensitive to painful mechanical stimuli, extreme heat or cold, and chemical stimuli. All mammalian nociceptors are free nerve endings.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 15.
A non-striated, elongated, spindle-shaped cell found lining the digestive tract, uterus, and blood vessels. They develop from specialized myoblasts (smooth muscle myoblast).
A muscle cell that has a fast contractile response. Fast muscle fibers make up the deep portion of the myotome and are also known as white muscle cells.
Multi-tissue structure forming the sides of the lumen of the neural tube in rhombomere 7.
The hypaxial region of somite 17 derived body wall muscle. The hypaxial region is ventral to the horizontal myoseptum.
The hypaxial region of somite 22 derived body wall muscle. The hypaxial region is ventral to the horizontal myoseptum.
The hypaxial region of somite 2 derived body wall muscle. The hypaxial region is ventral to the horizontal myoseptum.
Portion of the lateral forebrain bundle that lies in the telencephalon.
A CNS interneuron located in the spinal cord.
The hypaxial region of somite 9 derived body wall muscle. The hypaxial region is ventral to the horizontal myoseptum.
The hypaxial region of somite 6 derived body wall muscle. The hypaxial region is ventral to the horizontal myoseptum.
The hypaxial region of somite 30 derived body wall muscle. The hypaxial region is ventral to the horizontal myoseptum.
A Leydig cell is a testosterone-secreting cell in the interstitial area, between the seminiferous tubules, in the testis.
The hypaxial region of somite 28 derived body wall muscle. The hypaxial region is ventral to the horizontal myoseptum.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 12.
The hypaxial region of somite 25 derived body wall muscle. The hypaxial region is ventral to the horizontal myoseptum.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 5.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 3.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 8.
The hypaxial region of somite 14 derived body wall muscle. The hypaxial region is ventral to the horizontal myoseptum.
The hypaxial region of somite 11 derived body wall muscle. The hypaxial region is ventral to the horizontal myoseptum.
Portion of tissue which is part of the valvula cerebelli and consists largely of axons and dendrites.
Floor plate that is part of the rhombomere 8.
Floor plate that is part of the rhombomere 5.
Floor plate that is part of the rhombomere 2.
Cranial neural crest that gives rise to the facio-acoustic ganglion.
Portion of tissue that is dorsolateral to the floor plate and part of the midbrain.

comments: No metanephrose in zebrafish. Consider nephrogenic mesenchyme stem cell ZFA:0009187.

definition.val: A cell of the neural crest. The neural crest is a strip of specialized ectoderm, the neural plate border, which flanks each side of the embryonic neural plate. Neural crest cells are multipotent. Premigratory neural crest cells are found at the neural plate boarder, some of which will undergo ectomesenchymal transition and delamination to form migratory neural crest cells. Most of the cranial and all of the spinal sensory ganglion cells arise by differentiation of neural crest cells.

Islands of eosinic cells found on the lateroventral surface of the kidney. Function is thought to be that of the parathyroid gland in other vertebrates, which are lacking in fishes. These cells secrete hypocalcin (teleocalcin) to regulate calcium metabolism.
Embryonic structure, part of the neural keel, that gives rise to rhombomere 2.
Embryonic structure, part of the neural keel, that gives rise to rhombomere 1.
Meckel's cartilage is the bilaterally paired, rod-like, cartilaginous ventral component of the lower jaw, or ventral mandibular arch. It is typically resorbed in adults.
Region of the mesoderm that is located along the rostral-caudal axis of the embryo.

Multi-tissue structure that attach the zonules, that suspend the lens, to the eye.  The ciliary zone secretes aqueous humor.  Unlike mammals zebrafish the ciliary zone dose not contain processes or a circumferential band of muscle.

comments:
May need to obsolete this term, ZDB-PUB-050701-15.

The ciliary "body" does not contain processes or a cumferential band of muscle. For this reason, we refer to the region adjacent and posterior to the iris as the ciliary zone, and not the ciliary body. The ciliary zone, however, is expanded and has a morphology consistent with contraction in a small area of the ventral-most region.

definition.val: Multi-tissue structure that is comprised of neural and non-neural epithelial layers which will form the retina and retinal pigmented epithelium of the mature eye.

Primary sensory neurons with cell bodies located in the dorsal spinal cord, that innervate the integument of the trunk and tail at early larval stages. The cutaneous axons of Rohon-Beard neurons display a broad spectrum of peripheral axon branching patterns.  Most Rohon-Beard neurons undergo apoptosis by 5dpf.
A mature sexual reproductive cell having a single set of unpaired chromosomes.
An acidophilic cell of the anterior pituitary that produces growth hormone, somatotropin.

An epidermal cell which synthesizes keratin and undergoes a characteristic change as it moves upward from the basal layers of the epidermis to the cornified (horny) layer of the skin. Successive stages of differentiation of the keratinocytes forming the epidermal layers are basal cell, spinous or prickle cell, and the granular cell.

A mononuclear phagocyte present in variety of tissues, typically differentiated from monocytes, capable of phagocytosing a variety of extracellular particulate material, including immune complexes, microorganisms, and dead cells.
Any cell capable of ingesting particulate matter via phagocytosis.
A type of lymphocyte whose defining characteristic is the expression of an immunoglobulin complex.

Is a hindbrain interneuron.  Giant reticulospinal neurons possessing thick crossed axons and positioned dorsally in the hindbrain tegmentum at the level of entrance of the eighth cranial nerve.  The Mauthner neuron is paired. The M-cell has two large invariant dendrites: The lateral dendrite terminates in the sensory neuropil of the acoustico-lateral area, and the ventral dendrite terminates in the neuropil of the motor tegmentum. Fine dendrites are present, and mostly arise from three regions; from the terminus of each major dendrite and from the ventral surface of the perikaryon.

A non-neuronal cells of the nervous system. They not only provide physical support, but also respond to injury, regulate the ionic and chemical composition of the extracellular milieu. Form the myelin insulation of nervous pathways, guide neuronal migration during development, and exchange metabolites with neurons. Neuroglia have high-affinity transmitter uptake systems, voltage-dependent and transmitter-gated ion channels, and can release transmitters, but their role in signaling (as in many other functions) is unclear.

A modified epidermal cell located in the stratum basale. They are found mostly in areas where sensory perception is acute. Merkel cells are closely associated with an expanded terminal bulb of an afferent myelinated nerve fiber.
A cell within an epithelial cell sheet whose main function is to act as an internal or external covering for a tissue or an organism.

A supporting cell projecting inward from the basement membrane of seminiferous tubules. They surround and nourish the developing male germ cells and secrete androgen binding protein. Their tight junctions with the spermatogonia and spermatocytes provide a blood-testis barrier.
A cell whose primary function is to prevent the transport of stuff across compartments.
A cell of the middle germ layer of the embryo.
A cell of the outer of the three germ layers of the embryo.
A cell that moves by its own activities.
A neuroglial cell of the peripheral nervous system which forms the insulating myelin sheaths of peripheral axons.
A cell of the inner of the three germ layers of the embryo.
Multi-tissue structure which is the ventral region of the median tuberal portion of the hypothalamus and is the most rostral region of the hypothalamus. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
The posterior intestine has short longitudinally arranged epithelial folds which are similar to the colon of higher vertebrates.
The efferent motor portion of the spinal nerve root.
Deep, narrow muscle that arises anteriorly and laterally of the pelvic abductor profundus. It attaches to the first pelvic ray.
Trigeminal motor nucleus that is located at the ventrolateral edge of the lateral longitudinal fascicle.
Hindbrain motor nucleus which is the origin of motor axons of cranial nerve VI. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
The portion of the YSL that lies deep to the blastoderm during epiboly.

A multilayer of deep cells of fairly uniform thickness that forms during early epiboly (at dome stage; upon conversion of the blastodisc to the blastoderm); during gastrulation the DEL (deep cell layer) gives rise to the epiblast and hypoblast.

Brain structure that lies perpendicular to the longitudinal axis of the embryonic neural tube, is continuous with the rostral hypothalamic proliferation and whose most lateral extent is deflected dorsally within the inferior lobe.
Muscle that is important in controlling the leading edge of the pectoral fin in the juvenile zebrafish, particularly during the initiation of the downstroke.

comments: Acts as antagonist to the dorsal arrector.

definition.val: Otolith organ comprised of the macula utricle and lapillus. The lagena is part of the pars superior. The utricle functions in the detection of movement.
The epaxial region of somite 9 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.
The epaxial region of somite 6 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.
The epaxial region of somite 30 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 27.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 24.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 21.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 19.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 16.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 13.
The epaxial region of somite 8 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.
Fast muscle cell located in somite 10.
The epaxial region of somite 11 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.

Extraocular muscle innervated by the trochlear nerve.  The dorsal rectus and dorsal oblique muscles have overlapping insertions at the scleral-corneal junction on the dorsal side of the adult eye, though they have distinct insertion sites in 5dpf fish.   The dorsal oblique originates separately from the rectus muscles. The unsegmented paraxial head mesoderm contributes to the dorsal oblique muscles.   All the oblique extraocular muscles originate together from the anterior ethmoid plate.

comments: Mature form at Larval:Protruding-mouth.

definition.val: Skeletal system that is part of the head, including the splanchnocranium, chondrocranium, and dermatocranium.
The epaxial region of somite 28 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.
The epaxial region of somite 25 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.
The epaxial region of somite 22 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.
The epaxial region of somite 2 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum
The epaxial region of somite 17 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.
The epaxial region of somite 14 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.
The epaxial region of somite 5 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.
The epaxial region of somite 3 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk segment 2 or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk segment 17 or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk segment 14 or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk segment 11 or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome.

Paired, ventromedially directed processes on the posterior ends of the centra, ligamentously joined to the hemal postzygapophyses of the immediately posterior vertebra. The most posterior caudal vertebrae lack hemal postzygapophyses.
Vertebra which are the three most posterior vertebra supporting the caudal fin.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk segment 7 or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk segment 3 or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early tail segment 27 or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early tail segment 23 or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome.
A muscle cell that is small, darkly colored, with high lipid and mitochondrial content. Slow muscle cells are located superficial to the fast muscle cell in the myotome of somite 21.
The epaxial region of somite 27 derived body wall muscle. The epaxial region is dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum.
Apical ectodermal ridge that is part of the median fin fold.

nodes.lbl: apical ectodermal ridge median fin fold

definition.val: Artery that is part of the pharyngeal arches 3-5, and forms the afferent portion of a loop off of the aortic arch.
Hyoid muscle that originates at the opercle and subopercle and inserts into the branchiostegal rays.  The adductor hyohyoid is responsible for constriction of the branchiostegal membrane.
Diencephalic nucleus that is part of the central pretectum and lies dorsolateral to the caudal pretectal nucleus. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
A muscle cell that is small, darkly colored, with high lipid and mitochondrial content. Slow muscle cells are located superficial to the fast muscle cell in the myotome of somite 8.
A muscle cell that is small, darkly colored, with high lipid and mitochondrial content. Slow muscle cells are located superficial to the fast muscle cell in the myotome of somite 5.
A muscle cell that is small, darkly colored, with high lipid and mitochondrial content. Slow muscle cells are located superficial to the fast muscle cell in the myotome of somite 3.
A muscle cell that is small, darkly colored, with high lipid and mitochondrial content. Slow muscle cells are located superficial to the fast muscle cell in the myotome of somite 27.
A muscle cell that is small, darkly colored, with high lipid and mitochondrial content. Slow muscle cells are located superficial to the fast muscle cell in the myotome of somite 24.

Portion of the iris which contains  bundles of fibers, most of which are oriented radially around the pupil. The stroma is innervated by the iris blood vessels and develops from the periocular mesenchyme.
Blood vessels within the stroma of the iris.  The vessels cluster  and are more dense at the base of the stroma where the iris is thicker.
Portion of organism substance that is a gelatinous extracellular matrix structure that fills the vitreous cavity of the eye.
Joint that articulates the parasphenoid and basioccipital. Parasphenoid-basioccipital joint is paired.
Multi-tissue structure that composes the opaque fibrous outer layer of the eye.
Acellular anatomical structure that is the innermost layer of the optic choroid.
A specialized hair cell that has an elongated kinocilium upon which an otolith accretes. The tether cell then anchors the otolith in place.
Clear ocular fluid in the anterior segment of the eye.  It is produced primarily by dorsal ciliary epithelial cells.
Anatomical cluster comprising the caudal portion of the eye: the retina, posterior chamber, optic choroid, and vitreous.
Anatomical cluster comprising the rostral portion of the eye;  the cornea, lens, iris, ciliary zone, anterior chamber, and annular ligament.
Supraneural 3 is an elongated cartilage or cartilage replacement bone above vertebrae 3 and 4, developmentally fusing with NA 3 and 4. A crest or blade of membrane bone forms from its dorsal surface.

Supraneural 2 is an ovoid cartilage or cartilage replacement bone located above centrum 2. It forms an immovable joint with supraneural 3 and contributes to the neural complex roofing the neural canal.
The first four vertebrae, which are part of the Weberian apparatus.
Anatomical space that is the concavity containing the eye.

Brain structure which is a short stalk connecting the neurohypophysis with the brain. Axons of secretory cells in the floor of the diencephalon traverse the infundibulum and terminate in the neurohypophysis.
Third lepidotrichium of pelvic fin.
Portion of tissue that gives rise to the adenohypophysis.
Caudal portion of the adenohypophysis.
Portion of vessel wall that extends to form a new vessel.

comments: This structure does not exist in Zebrafish.  Consider proximal pars anterior ZFA:0005581.

definition.val: The anterior portion of the adenohypophysis. Comprised of the proximal and rostral pars anterior.
Neural crest that is part of the head.
Supraneural located between vertebra 7 and 8.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the sixth most anterior pectoral ray, usually branched and segmented.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the fifth most anterior pectoral ray , usually branched and segmented.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the seventh most anterior pectoral ray, usually branched and segmented.
First lepidotrichium of pelvic fin.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the fourth most anterior pectoral ray, usually branched and segmented.
Fourth lepidotrichium of pelvic fin.
Second lepidotrichium of pelvic fin.

The tissue which lies between the basal stratum and the superficial stratum.   This layer is composed of a variable number of cell layers which contain  mucous goblet cells, club cells and sensory cells.  Most of the cells of this region are undifferentiated. They serve as a reservoir to replace dead cells in any of the epidermis regions.

Lower layer of the epidermis. Composed of a single layer of cells.  The major function of the basal stratum is to keep the epidermis attached to the underlying dermis by means of (hemidesmosomes attached to the basement membrane.

All serially repeated ossified, cartilaginous, and ligamentous elements around the notochord (Schultze and Arratia, 1988).  Adult zebrafish usually 32 vertebrae but may have as few as 30 to as many as 33 vertebrae.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium 1 is the leading or marginal ray of the fin and articulates with the scapula.  Lepidotrichium 1 is commonly segmented but unbranched.
Actinotrichium that is part of the pelvic fin.

The Weberian apparatus consists of the modified anteriormost four vertebrae and associated structures of otophysans which transduce sound or pressure waves from the tunica externa of the swim bladder to the inner ear (Alexander, 1962).
Embryonic structure that gives rise to the midbrain hindbrain boundary.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the third most anterior pectoral ray, usually branched and segmented.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the second most anterior pectoral ray, usually branched and segmented.

Acellular anatomical structure that is a layer of collagen fibrils in the immature integument in a subepidermal space. At first, the fibrils are all oriented in the same direction, later they form the complex plywood-like structure that is characteristic of the dermal deep region.

The outermost epidermal layer covering the fish at embryonic stages; derived from the EVL and thought to eventually be replaced by the superficial stratum of the epidermis. Sometimes used synonymously with EVL.
Paired fin located in the abdominal position of the body.
Outer portion of the dermis composed of a loose collagenous matrix housing numerous fibroblasts, nerves, some pigment cells, and scales.  Scale development takes place in this layer of the dermis.
Portion of the dermis characterized by a well-arranged, plywood-like, collagenous network.
Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the fourth centrum.
Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the third centrum.
Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the sixth centrum.
Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the fifth centrum.
Actinotrichium that is part of the pectoral fin.
Joint that articulates the hyomandibular cartilage or bone and otic region cartilage or sphenotic bone, and often pterotic bone and prootic bone. Hyomandibular-otic region joint is paired.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 3.
Anatomical space between bones of the neurocranium.  Frequently closes during development.
Anal fin lepidotrichium that is distally branched.

Embryonic structure that is composed of the cellular part of the embryo, excluding the yolk cell, derived from the blastodisc by early morphogenesis; refers particularly to the time when the cell array is sheet-like, between 30%-epiboly and the end of gastrulation.
Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the first centrum.
Embryonic structure that is the dome of cytoplasm that segregates from the yolk toward the animal pole during and after the one cell-stage, and which undergoes cleavage.
Fontanel within the frontal bone near the frontal-sphenotic joint. Lateral fontanel of frontal is paired.
Epithelium lining the pharynx consisting largely of simple columnar epithelium with a short segment (1mm) of stratified squamous epithelium on the ventral side.
Median fin that is located on the dorsal surface of the fish.
Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the second centrum.

Cartilaginous larval structure dorsal to the four anterior-most vertebrae, which forms the connection between neural arches and supraneurals in the Weberian apparatus.  Located dorsal to the neural tube.

Thin, rod-shaped, anteroventrally directed membrane bone that develops as a separate outgrowth  from the cartilage parapophysis of the fourth vertebra; develops ventrally to curve around the anterior head of the swim bladder. It articulates with the tripus at the tripus-swim bladder connection. Often termed a fifth Weberian ossicle.

comments: The os suspensorium is similar in shape to a rib, but the other ribs in Danio develop as separate ossifications that grow toward and articulate with the parapophyses.

definition.val: Scale that is associated with the lateral line sensory canal.

Dermal bone that is located on or subjacent to the surface anywhere on the body and that is not part of the general complement of scales, dermal bone of the dermatocranium, postcranial axial skeleton or paired fin skeleton. Bony plate may exist singly, or as unpaired or paired clusters or series.
The bony shelf above orbit is an anatomical cluster formed by the dorsolateral portions of the lateral ethmoid, frontal and sphenotic bones that forms the dorsal margin of the orbit.
Dorsal fin ray that is distally branched.

The outer layer of the epidermis.  The living cells form single cell layer, the outer surface of which is ornamented with microridges. These outer epidermal cells are not renewed periodically, but are individually replaced when dead.
Caudal fin lepidotrichium that is distally branched.
Developing nephron where the developing glomerular capsule has been invaded by a glomerular capillary loop called the glomerular tuft.
A branched nephron of the mature kidney.
Renal duct that will develop into the mesonephric distal tubule.
Non-material anatomical entity of two dimensions, that is demarcated by anatomical lines or points on the external or internal surfaces of anatomical structures.
An anatomical structure that is regional part of the central nervous system where there is a significant bend of the axis.
Fin that is one of a pair located ventrally on the organism.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 12.
Ghrelin secreting cells found in the found in the exocrine pancreas.

comments: In mammals the endocrine pancreas is called the Islets of Langerhans.

definition.val: Fin that is an unpaired fin located in the sagittal plane of the organism.
A cell that secretes ghrelin, the peptide hormone that stimulates hunger.

Caudal portion of pars anterior of the adenohypophysis where somatotropes, thyrotropes and gonadotropes are localized.  The proximal pars anterior has functional homology to the mammalian pars tuberalis, secreting the same hormones.
Rostral portion of pars anterior of the adenohypophysis where corticotropes and lactotropes localize.
Cluster of cells along the center of  the neural plate that have the potential to become neuroblast.
Cluster of cells along the edge of  the neural plate that have the potential to become neuroblast.
Renal duct that will develop into the mesonephric proximal tubule.
Anatomical cluster which give rise to mature mesonephric nephrons.  Zebrafish continously generate new mesonephric nephrons.
Cluster of cells comprising a portion of tissue which gives rise to new mesonephric nephrons.  The cluster contains self-renewing stem cells.
Hollow cluster of epithelial cells derived from the nephron progenitor.
Developing nephron with a tubular morphology that has a renal corpuscle anlage at the distal end.
Developing nephron with a comma shaped appearance.
The line where the cornea and the sclera meet.
Integument ionocyte rich in Na-Cl co-transporter (NCC) activity.
Head mesenchyme surrounding the immature eye that  gives rise to specialized structures of the anterior segment of the eye.
Duct present in the angle where the cornea meets the ciliary zone that absorbs the aqueous humor.
The lens capsule is a modified basement membrane that completely surrounds the ocular lens.

Modified or toughened vitreous that suspend the lens at the equator to the non-pigmented epithelium of the ciliary zone.  In zebrafish, dorsal zonules are thickened as compared to ventral zonules. In both dorsal and ventral regions, these fibers delimit the vitreous body aqueous humor boundary.
Brain nuclei located in the ventral thalamus.
Portion of tissue that are compact accumulations of neurons having roughly similar connections and functions.
The multi-tissue structure that is the beginning of the spinal nerve leaving the spinal cord.
Skeletogenic cell that produces enamel, overlies the odontogenic papilla, and arises from the differentiation of a preameloblast cell.

comments: Was CL:0000139, seems that cell type was merged into CL:0000059 along with CL:0000053.

definition.val: Polymorphic cell that form cartilage.

A mature osteoblast that has become embedded in the bone matrix. They occupy a small cavity, called lacuna, in the matrix and are connected to adjacent osteocytes via protoplasmic projections called canaliculi.
A cell capable of processing and presenting lipid and protein antigens to T cells in order to initiate an immune response.

comments: Note change of name; nearly all somatic cells can present antigens to T cells via MHC Class I complexes leading to effector responses, but professional antigen presenting cells constitutively express MHC Class II as well as constimulatory molecules, and thus can initiate immune responses via T cells.

definition.val: An osteocytelike cell with numerous processes, trapped in a lacuna in the cement of the tooth.

A fat-storing cell found mostly in the abdominal cavity and subcutaneous tissue of mammals. Fat is usually stored in the form of triglycerides. Cell that stores fat in a unilocular lipid droplet, has a thin circular cytoplasm and pericentral nucleus. The average adult adipocyte diameter is between 30 and 40 micrometers.  No adipocytes were observed in larvae on 6 or 9 dpf.
A cell that normally gives rise to other cells that are organized as three-dimensional masses, rather than sheets.
Postcranial axial skeleton that is unpaired and located on the sagittal plane of the organism.
Portion of tissue that consists of a layer of cells that form during embryogenesis that will give rise to all structures of the organism.
Presumptive structure fated to become the shield.  Defined by fate mapping.
Sensory system responsible for the perception of light.

The NEM cell cluster lies in a superficial position of the dorsal blastoderm margin encompassing EVL cells and one or two layers of underlying deep cells. Unlike other marginal blastomeres, cells in this cluster do not participate in involution.
The dorsal marginal region of the YSL where maternal dorsal determinants localize.  Participates in positioning the shield.
Median fin skeleton located on the dorsal surface of the organism.

A class of large neuroglial (macroglial) cells in the central nervous system - the largest and most numerous neuroglial cells in the brain and spinal cord. Astrocytes (from 'star' cells) are irregularly shaped with many long processes, including those with 'end feet' which form the glial (limiting) membrane and directly and indirectly contribute to the blood-brain barrier. They regulate the extracellular ionic and chemical environment, and 'reactive astrocytes' (along with microglia) respond to injury.

A non-neuronal cell of the nervous system. They not only provide physical support, but also respond to injury, regulate the ionic and chemical composition of the extracellular milieu. Guide neuronal migration during development, and exchange metabolites with neurons.
Cell of the single layer of large flattened cells covering the surface of the cornea.
A central nervous system macrophage found in the parenchyma of the central nervous system.
A class of large neuroglial (macroglial) cells in the central nervous system. Form the insulating myelin sheath of axons in the central nervous system.
The output neuron of the cerebellar cortex.
Portion of tissue part of the ovarian follicle containing a single layer of granulosa cells that surround the developing oocyte.
Acellular anatomic structure that is a layer that  separates the developing oocyte and the granulosa cell layer.

Oocyte development of zebrafish has been divided into five stages based on morphological criteria and on physiological and biochemical events. Stage I follicles (less than 140 microns) are primary growth stage, stage II follicles (140-340 microns) are cortical alveolus stage, stage III (340-690 microns) are vitellogenesis, stage IV (690-730 microns) are oocyte maturation, and stage V follicles are matured egg.
A collagenous layer of the skin subjacent to the epidermis and covering the hypodermis. It contains various types of cells (e.g. fibroblasts, pigment cells, nerve, blood vessels and scales.
A protuberance in front of the gential pore and behind the vent. Mature females have a well developed urogenital papillae whilst in mature males it is poorly developed.
Organism subdivision which is the part of the body posterior to the vent which includes the anal and caudal fins.
Portion of embryonic tissue determined by fate mapping to become a structure.
Organism subdivision which is the part of the body posterior to the head and anterior to the post-vent region.
Organism subdivision which is the part of the body which consists of the cranial and pharyngeal regions.
Multi-tissue structure of the ovarian follicle, composed of stromal cells and capillaries that covers oocytes.  The thecal layer is external to the granulosa cell layer.
A vertebrate phagocyte with a single nucleus.

Pioneer neurons establish a pathway in the developing central nervous system and then undergo programmed cell death once the adult axons, which follow them, have made connections with the target site. Thus, they are a transient cell type involved in axon guidance.
A neuron that uses acetylcholine as a vesicular neurotransmitter.
Sensory system that uses taste buds to sense chemical compounds.
A duct that carries bile from the liver to the intestine.
A female germ cell that has entered meiosis.

comments: I think the term we really want is CL:0000023.

definition.val: Telencephalic white matter (commissure) which connects the two cerebral hemispheres across the midline.
Portion of tissue that develops into a gill.
Outpocketings of pharyngeal endoderm that interdigitate with the neural crest derived pharyngeal arches. The pouches later fuse with the surface ectoderm to form the gill slits.
Anatomical structure that is part of the embryo and is comprised of portions of tissue or cells.
An efferent neuron that passes from the central nervous system or a ganglion toward or to a muscle and conducts an impulse that causes movement.

Most generally any neuron which is not motor or sensory. Interneurons may also refer to neurons whose axons remain within a particular brain region as contrasted with projection neurons which have axons projecting to other brain regions.
A type of interneuron that has two neurites, usually an axon and a dendrite, extending from opposite poles of an ovoid cell body.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to the neurocranium.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 14.
Supraneural located between vertebra 8 and 9.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 13.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 16.
Supraneural located between  vertebra 4 and 5.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 15.
Supraneural located between vertebra 5 and 6.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 18.
Supraneural located between vertebra 6 and 7.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 17.
Median fin that is located posterior to the anus.
Paired fin that is located in the thoracic region of the body.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 9.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 8.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 2.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 11.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 10.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 1.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 1.
Dorsolateral placode that gives rise to the posterior lateral line.

Nervous system that  is involved primarily with the internal regulation of the gustatory processes. In most vertebrates the enteric neurons form two layers of ganglionic plexuses located along the entire length of the gastrointestinal tract.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 2.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 4.
Musculature part of the anal fin.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 3.
Placode that develops into a tooth. The placode is a thickening of the pharyngeal epithelium.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 6.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is posterior to tooth 2MD and anterior to tooth 4MD in the mediodorsal tooth row.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is the posteriormost tooth in the mediodorsal tooth row.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 5.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is the posteriormost tooth in the dorsal tooth row.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 7.
Shallow area that exists on the prootic.
System that provides protection against foreign and abnormal cells and removes cellular debris.
Caudal principal ray that is the dorsalmost caudal principal ray of the caudal fin.
Anatomical system that produces, transports and secretes peptides.

A migrating group of cells originating from the posterior lateral line placode.  The primordium deposits seven to nine neuromasts and interneuromasts between them during its posterior migration to the tail.
Dermal bone that is ring-shaped or cylindrical and surrounds a sensory canal.
Lateral ethmoid-ectopterygoid ligament is a ligament that connects the lateral ethmoid to the ectopterygoid.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is posterior to tooth 2V and anterior to tooth 4V in the ventral tooth row.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is posterior to tooth 1V and anterior to tooth 3V in the ventral tooth row.
Lateral ethmoid-autopalatine ligament is a ligament that connects the lateral ethmoid to the autopalatine.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is posterior to tooth 3V and anterior to tooth 5V in the ventral tooth row.
Joint between the centra, and sometimes the neural arches or parapophyses.
Joint between the centra, and sometimes the neural arches or parapophyses of vertebra 4 and vertebra 5.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is the posteriormost tooth in the ventral tooth row.
Multi-tissue structure composed of connective tissue that surrounds, the internal portions of the olfactory epithelium.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is the anteriormost tooth in the ventral tooth row.
Joint between the centra, and sometimes the neural arches or parapophyses of vertebra 6 and vertebra 7.
Tooth row that is the dorsalmost row of teeth on ceratobranchial 5 bone.
Anatomical cluster that is the upper roof of the mouth that is roofed by bones such as the parasphenoid, prevomer, metapterygoid, orbitosphenoid.

Mental barbel that originates on the chin, in an anteromedial position relative to the outer mental barbel. The inner mental barbel is nearer to the mandibular symphysis than is the outer mental barbel.
Sensory system responsible for olfaction.  Olfaction involves the detection of chemical composition of an organism's ambient medium by chemoreceptors.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is the anteriormost tooth in the dorsal tooth row.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is posterior to tooth 1MD and anterior to tooth 3MD in the mediodorsal tooth row.
Interopercular-mandibular ligament is a ligament that connects the interopercle to the retroarticular element of the lower jaw.

comments: The interopercle ossifies in the interoperculomandibular ligament, which attaches to the retroarticular. The interopercle approximates and is ligamentously attached to the retroarticular anteroventrally. ZDB-PUB-961014-192.  Need develops_in relationship for interopercle.

definition.val: Is a bony partially gas filled sphere located ventral and anterior to the inner ear.  The prootic bulla is paired.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is the anteriormost tooth in the mediodorsal tooth row.
An endocrine cell that is located in the epithelium of the gastrointestinal tract.
A cell of an endocrine gland, ductless glands that secrete substances which are released directly into the circulation and which influence metabolism and other body functions.
A cell of the epithelial lining that produce and secrete mucins.

A cell that stores epinephrine secretory vesicles. During times of stress, the nervous system signals the vesicles to secrete their hormonal content. Their name derives from their ability to stain a brownish color with chromic salts. Characteristically, they are located in the adrenal medulla and paraganglia of the sympathetic nervous system.
A neuron that has the specialized function to produce and secrete hormones, and that constitutes, in whole or in part, an endocrine organ or system.
A cell of an exocrine gland, i.e. a gland that discharges its secretion via a duct.
A pigment cell derived from the neural crest. Contains melanin-filled pigment granules, which gives a brown to black appearance.
Tooth row that is the mediodorsal row of teeth on ceratobranchial 5 bone, located between the dorsal tooth row and ventral tooth row.
Sensory system responsible for the perception of spatial orientation and auditory stimuli.
Tooth row that is the ventralmost row of teeth on ceratobranchial 5 bone.
A layer separating the inner face of the dermis from the subjacent muscle cells. It is covered on both sides by a basement membrane.  It contains pigment cells.
Portion of tissue that is the cavity-containing primordium of the central nervous system, developing from the neural rod in the late segmentation period.
An embryonic cell that is formed before the germ layers have been formed.
Anatomical structure that has as its parts a maximally connected cell compartment surrounded by a plasma membrane.

The hyomandibula is the large, dorsal-most member of the hyoid arch.  It begins ossifying in the dorsal edge of the hyosymplectic cartilage near the hyomandibular foramen (4.6 mm NL). Ossification spreads through the cartilage, and sheets of membrane bone form off the cartilage model anteriorly and posteriorly (6.6 mm). In the adult, the hyomandibula has cartilage-capped anterior and posterior articulating heads that meet the sphenotic-prootic fossa and the pterotic fossa, respectively, in synovial joints.  A posterior knob of bone develops, also capped in cartilage, and it forms a synovial joint with the opercle.
A connective tissue partition developing at the apex of the chevron-shaped myotome and separating dorsal (epaxial) and ventral (hypaxial) body wall muscle masses.
Vein that carries blood away from the liver.
A mature male germ cell that develops from a spermatid.
A male germ cell that develops from spermatogonia. The euploid primary spermatocytes undergo meiosis and give rise to the haploid secondary spermatocytes which in turn give rise to spermatids.
Specialized neuronal receptor cells of the anterior macula. (Also see Anatomical Atlas entry for hair cells by T. Whitfield.)
A cell of the trunk neural crest.
A cell of the cranial neural crest.
Otolith that is part of the sacculus.
Dermal bone that is located anterior to the subopercle and lying below and slightly ventral to the horizontal limb of the preopercle. The interopercle is a paired bone.

A pair of HA are connect one to each AA1. They run rostromedially until at the extreme rostro-ventral midline the two vessels merge and then run straight caudally along the ventral midline until they reach the cranial end of the ventral aorta (VA). There, the single HA passes just dorsal to the rostral end of the VA and then immediately splits again into a pair of HA. The paired HA continue caudally just to either side of the ventral midline. The HA provide blood supply to the ventral branchial region and the heart.
An euploid male germ cell of an early stage of spermatogenesis.

Paired cartilage bone that bears a large foramen (lateral occipital foramen).  Contacts the supraoccipital dorsally, the epiotic laterally and the basioccipital ventrally. Forms the posterior hind margin of the cranium and borders the lateral and posterior margins of the forum (foramen) magnum.

A free, modified neural spine of a preural or a ural vertebra that is placed between the last developed neural spine of a preural centrum and the dorsal axis (= anterior margin of first uroneural) of the caudal skeleton . An epural commonly supports one or more dorsal procurrent rays. An epural is an unpaired median perichondrally ossified bone.
The zebrafish head kidney consists of fused bilateral lobes located in the anterior part of the kidney.  It is analogous to the mammalian bone marrow and the primary site of definitive hematopoiesis.

Cranial nerve that innervates gill muscles.  Sometimes called a branchiomeric nerve because it innervates derivatives of the branchial arches.  The root is typically found at rhombomere 6.  This nerve contains sensory axons that carry both somatic and visceral sensory information as well as motor axons from branchiomotor neurons.
Portion of tissue that projects outward from the gill and is a thread-like, soft, red respiratory and excretory structure.
Artery of the gill filament.
Cranial nerve where motor axons innervate muscles derived from the second branchial arch. The motor neurons are generated in rhombomere 4.

Dermal canal-bearing bone placed at the dorso-posterior region of the skull roof, lying on the posterior region of the pterotic and parietals, or the pterotic and epioccipital, or on the pterotic, epioccipital and occipital bones.

Musculature that is part of the dorsal fin.  The dorsal fin musculature is composed of one unit per fin ray that are arranged in series on each side of the body. Each unit is composed of one fin ray, three supporting pterygophores, and a set of paired depressor, erector, and inclinator muscles.

Pharyngeal arch bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial cartilage or bone. Epibranchials are dorsal parts of the gill arches. Epibranchials 1-4 ossify in the epibranchial cartilages in a posterior to anterior progression. Gill rakers are present on the anterior and posterior edges of epibranchials 2 and 4 and the posterior edge of epibranchial 1. A reduced gill raker is present on the anterior margin of epibranchial 1 in some specimens.

The entopterygoid is a dermal bone that forms the anteroventral and ventral surface of the orbit. It develops as a long sliver of bone developing in the membrane dorsomedial to the palatoquadrate cartilage (3.8 mm NL).

The ectopterygoid is dermal bone located at the anterior part of the palatoquadrate.  It is first visible as a very thin ossification along the anteroventral border of the palatoquadrate cartilage (6.4 mm). In adults it is a long sliver of bone that is narrow anteriorly where it meets the entopterygoid in a synostosis. It is slightly wider at its posterior synostosis with the quadrate.
Abducens motor nucleus which is located at the level of the superior reticular formation.
Multi-tissue structure that is the dorsal part of the thalamus and emerges ventral to the caudal portion of the ventral habenular nucleus. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
The afferent sensory portion of the spinal nerve root.
Dorsal pelvic fin muscle that originates at the anterior side of the basipterygium and inserts onto the base of the first pelvic fin ray.
Cerebellar commissure that runs between the bulbo-spinal tract and the vestibulo-spinal tract.

synonyms.val: commissure of the secondary gustatory nuclei

nodes.lbl: commissure of the secondary gustatory nucleus

definition.val: Anterior commissure which is located immediately ventral to the supracommissural nucleus of area ventralis telencephali. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
Postcranial axial cartilage and Weberian ossicle that is located dorsal to the scaphium. The claustrum is bilaterally paired.
Diencephalic nucleus which is located in the caudal portion of the dorsal thalamus, dorsal to the central caudal thalamic nucleus.
Rod-like internal median skeletal support bones of the anal fin, which articulate with the lepidotrichia distally.

comments:
"Dermal tooth plates are variable structures.  During upper pharyngeal arch development in Astatotilapia elegans, dermal tooth plates are formed entirely of fused tooth pedicels (Huys-seune, 1983). However, in lower pharyngeals of the same species, teeth attach to a preexisting plate (Vandewalle et al., 1994). In other teleosts (e.g., cyprinid fifth ceratobranchials), there is no tooth plate per se, because tooth pedicels do not fuse to one another, but each fuses to the endochondral bone separately (see Gosline, 1985)."
Consider ZFA:0001239  ceratobranchial 5 bone or ZFA:0000694 ceratobranchial 5 tooth

definition.val: CNS white matter comprised of the rostral mesencephalo-cerebellar and caudal mesencephalo-cerebellar tracts. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.

nodes.lbl: decussation of the medial octavolateralis nucleus

definition.val: Twelve pairs of cranial nerves exit/enter the cranium through openings in the skull. The nerves contain efferent axons with motor and glandular functions, as well as afferent axons from cranial ganglia with sensory functions. The nerves are numbered in a rostral to caudal sequence, with the exception of the lateral line nerves.
Multi-tissue structure that forms the transparent front part of the eye, covering the iris, pupil and anterior chamber.
A type of lymphocyte whose defining characteristic is the expression of a T cell receptor complex.

comments: CL:0000804 and CL:0000812 were merged in the cell ontology into CL:0000084.

definition.val: A cell found predominately in the blood.
A cell which moves among different tissues of the body, via blood, lymph, or other medium.

A fully differentiated neutrophil, a granular leukocyte having a nucleus with three to five lobes connected by slender threads of chromatin, and cytoplasm containing fine inconspicuous granules and stainable by neutral dyes.
A leukocyte with abundant granules in the cytoplasm.
A specialized phagocytic cell associated with the absorption and removal of the mineralized matrix of bone tissue, which typically differentiates from monocytes.

comments: Morphology: Highly vesicular; markers: Surface: RANK, cFMS (MCSF receptor); Secreted: cathepsin K and TRAP (tartate resistant acid phosphatase); transcription factors: PU.1, cFOS, MITF, NFkB (p52); role or process: tissue remodelling: bone resorption; lineage: hematopoietic, myeloid.

definition.val: A bone-forming cell which secretes an extracellular matrix. Hydroxyapatite crystals are then deposited into the matrix to form bone.
A cell of ectomesenchymal origin concerned with the formation of the layer of cementum on the roots of teeth.
A cell that is usually found in a two-dimensional sheet with a free surface.
A neurectoderm derived cell that lines the neural lumen.
A stem cell that can give rise to mulitple lineages of cells.
A stem cell from which all cells of the body can form.
An oligopotent progenitor cell committed to the lymphoid lineage.
A progenitor cell committed to the megakaryocyte and erythroid lineages.
A progenitor cell committed to myeloid lineage, including the megakaryocyte and erythroid lineages.

synonyms.val: colony forming unit granulocyte, erythrocyte, macrophage, and megakaryocyte

definition.val: Is a multi-tissue structure composed of dentine, enameloid and tooth pulp. The tips of the ceratobranchial 5 teeth form before the ceratobranchial itself (3.0 mm NL). As they grow ventrally, they meet the perichondrally ossified surface of ceratobranchial 5 and become firmly ankylosed to the bone. Ceratobranchial teeth are the only teeth present in zebrafish and other cypriniforms.

The tangential nucleus is located in rhombomere 5 and receives a dense utricular input.   Tangential nucleus neurons project contralaterally to extraocular motoneurons and to multiple sites within the reticulospinal complex; unlike other classes of vestibular neuron, they modulate their firing in response to static head displacements.
The symplectic is an irregularly rod-shaped cartilage replacement bone articulating with the hyomandibular and quadrate.
Paired dermal bones that form the anterodorsal margin of the orbit.

A cylindrical epithelial cell in the innermost layer of the enamel organ. Their functions include contribution to the development of the dentinoenamel junction by the deposition of a layer of the matrix, thus producing the foundation for the prisms (the structural units of the dental enamel), and production of the matrix for the enamel prisms and interprismatic substance. (From Jablonski's Dictionary of Dentistry, 1992).

Skeletogenic cell that is typically non-terminally differentiated, secretes an avascular, GAG rich matrix; is not buried in cartilage tissue matrix, retains the ability to divide, located adjacent to cartilage tissue (including within the perichondrium).
A connective tissue cell which secretes an extracellular matrix rich in collagen and other macromolecules.

comments: Not in CL.

definition.val: An embryonic (precursor) cell of the myogenic lineage that develops from the mesoderm. They undergo proliferation, migrate to their various sites, and then differentiate into the appropriate form of myocytes.

comments: Ural ossification is a process not a structure, thus it belongs in GO biologyical process not ZFA.

definition.val: The fourth Weberian ossicle. The tripus is a complex modification of the parapophysis and rib of the third vertebra. Anteriorly it attaches to the interosseus ligament and posteriorly it extends as a transformator process embedded in the tunica externa of the swim bladder.
Cranial nerve which exits the medulla oblongata and carries both sensory and motor axons to and from the facial region. The root is typically found at rhombomere 2.

comments:
ZDB-PUB-040109-20
The motor neuron cell bodies arise in rhombomeres 2 and 3. The neurons in r2 extend axons dorsolaterally to their exit point. The axons of branchiomotor neuron cell bodies in r3 initially extend dorsolaterally, then turn rostrally to reach their exit point in r2. The anterior turn occurs where the motor axons meet the ingrowing trigeminal sensory axons.

definition.val: The anatomical space located between the lips and the oral valves.
Skeletogenic cell that  secretes dentine matrix, is derived from the tooth pulp.
Diencephalic nucleus that is part of the synencephalon, is located adjacent to the caudal commissure and contains ciliated neurosecretory ependymal cells. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
Paired, dorsomedially directed processes on the posterior ends of the centra, ligamentously joined to the neural prezygapophyses of the immediately posterior vertebra.
Heart valve that forms between the atrium and the sinus venosus.
A myeloid progenitor cell committed to the monocyte lineage.
A cell that is within the developmental lineage of gametes and is able to pass along its genetic material to offspring.
A progenitor cell committed to the erythroid lineage.
Periventricular nucleus which is contiguous with the caudal part of the dorsal nucleus of the ventral telencephalon and the postcommissural nucleus. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
A stem cell from which all cells of the lymphoid and myeloid lineages develop, including blood cells and cells of the immune system.

Supporting cell that is part of the olfactory epithelium. Their cell bodies are more or less cylindrical, often with a pronounced basal part resting on the basal lamina. Their apical surface is covered with microvillous-like protrusions. Nuclei of olfactory support cell lie below the nuclear layer of olfactory sensory neurons,  a feature that is reverse that of other vertebrates.  The nuclei are less electron dense then those of the olfactory sensory neurons.

comments: Different nuclear position and morphology from CL_0000853.

definition.val: Multi-tissue structure that is the superficial part of the pretectum and is embedded in the optic tract.

Abductor muscle that develops from the primitive pectoral fin abductor.  The  abductor superficialis originates along the anterior skeletal flange of the pectoral girdle, the bundles insert to fin ray base distal processes.
CNS white matter (commissure) that runs between the optic tectal hemispheres.

A myeloblast committed to the neutrophil lineage. A myeloblast is the most primitive precursor in the granulocytic series, having fine, evenly distributed chromatin, several nucleoli, and a nongranular basophilic cytoplasm.
Groove that is in the ventral optic cup remnant of the optic fissure.
Portion of tissue that will develop into the myocardium.
Fossa where the hyomandibula articulates with the sphenotic and prootic to form the hyomandibular-otic region joint.
Surface structure that is a portion of skin that projects or hangs from the body.
Organ entity that is typically involved in mechanical support and may have different skeletal tissue compositions at different stages.
Joint that articulates the epihyal and ceratohyal bones. Epihyal-ceratohyal joint is paired.
Surface structure that is the region of the head in front of and between the orbits, and above the lower jaw. Nares are located on the snout.
Fine ridges on surface of scale, often parallel to the circumference of scale.
Joint that articulates the epihyal and branchiostegal ray bones. Epihyal-branchiostegal ray joint is paired.
Abducens motor nucleus which is located at the level of the intermediate reticular formation.

Fin musculature that is part of the caudal fin.  The musculature is  composed of 12 muscles that are arranged in a superficial and a deep muscle layer. Nerve roots of spinal segments 27-31 supply the caudal fin muscles.

Endochondral bone that begins ossifying on the anterior surface of the posterior end of the ceratohyal cartilage near the site of articulation with the interhyal (5.8 mm). It joins the ceratohyal in a pad of persisting cartilage.

Brainstem and spinal tract which emerges medial to the caudal intermediate reticular formation and runs caudally along the medial edge of the inferior reticular formation. It is displaced laterally and associates with other tracts in the dorsal part of the funiculus lateralis immediately prior to reaching the spinal cord. The bulbo-spinal tract carries descending spinal projections. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
Portion of tissue composed of parallel fibers that originate at the granular eminence that overlays the rhombencephalic lateral line region. Also termed the molecular layer.

comments: Not sure how much of the molecular layer is cerebellar crest.

definition.val: Diencephalic nucleus that is part of the central pretectum and is dorsal to the magnocellular superficial pretectal nucleus and the caudal pretectal nucleus. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
Multi-tissue structure which forms most of the median tuberal portion of the hypothalamus. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
Brain structure which is part of the diencephalon and is larger than the dorsal thalamus and ventral thalamus. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
Anatomical system that has as its parts the organs concerned with reproduction.

Diencephalic nucleus that is part of the superficial pretectum and is rostrally contiguous with the magnocellular superficial pretectal nucleus. Cells of the caudal pretectal nucleus are slightly smaller and less orderly around a central neuropil than those of the magnocellular superficial pretectal nucleus. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
Diencephalic nucleus that is part of the preoptic area and is the posterior continuation of the rostral parvocellular preoptic nucleus. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.

Patch of thickened, pseudostratified epithelium that is associated with the anterior semicircular canal. It consists of regular arrays of sensory hair cells interspersed with supporting cells. The anterior crista has its own characteristic shape and polarity pattern. (See Anatomical Atlas entry for sensory patches of the ear by T. Whitfield.)

Brainstem commissure located immediately rostral to the interpeduncular nucleus. Many fibers in the tecto-bulbar tract cross the midline through the ansulate commissure. Referred to as the ventral tegmental commissure at embryonic stages, and is the only commissure to change names during development. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.

Series of muscles that have a distal attachment at the anteriolateral base of each ray and spike and a proximal attachment to the haemal spines.  A tendon runs along one third the dorsoventral length of the muscle toward the attachment at the haemal spine.  These muscles act in opposition to the anal depressors to raise the anal fin rays.

Small thin adductor muscle that is part of the pectoral fin. The origin of the adductor profundus lies along the developing anterior skeletal flange of the pectoral girdle.  The adductor profundus develops from the primitive pectoral fin adductor.

Hyoid muscle that originates at the parasphenoid and inserts into the mesial sides of the hyomandibula, metapterygoid and entopterygoid.  The Adductor arcus palatini is responsible for suspensorial adduction.

comments: Term is being obsoleted because it cannot be anatomically identified in zebrafish. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain ISBN:3764351209.

definition.val: Endochondral bone that is paired and supports the pelvic fin. The basipterygium has a posteromedial process called the ischiac process (Wietzman 1962).
Surface structure which is a tactile structure found in the branchial region. Barbels are covered with epidermis rich in taste buds, and are innervated by branches of the cranial nerves.

The quadrate is the dorsal bone in the jaw joint with the anguloarticular of the lower jaw. Ossification of the quadrate, a cartilage bone, begins as a posteriorly projecting membranous spine between the symplectic cartilage and the preopercle (5.1 mm NL). The body of the quadrate ossifies first at the ball-and-socket articulation with the anguloarticular (6.5 mm). The adult quadrate is shaped roughly like an inverted triangle with a long, posteriorly projecting spine off its posteroventral edge. The presence of a posteroventral or posterior process of the quadrate is a synapomorphy of Teleostei.

The cartilaginous autopalatine forms from the anterior palatoquadrate arch. The first sign of ossification is visible at the anterior tip where it articulates with the maxilla (7.6 mm). In adults there are three processes at the anterior portion of the palatine: a ventromedial process, which forms the socket of the small ball- and- socket joint with the preethmoid; a dorsomedial process, which is connected by a short ligament to the ethmoid; and a lateral process, which extends toward the first infraorbital. Possession of a dorsomedial process, which abuts the ethmoid, is a unique feature shared by Cypriniformes (Fink and Fink, 1981). The palatine has two components, the autopalatine (derived from pars autopalatine) and the dermal component having teeth, the dermopalatine Arratia & Schultze 1990. The element in cypriniforms is only the cartilage part, so that it is more correct to name it autopalatine and not as palatine in general that it implies a fusion of elements (as in perciforms).
Midbrain nucleus which is part of the torus semicircularis and is the target of ascending octavolateralis systems related to mechanoreception. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
Brainstem commissure that intersects the medial longitudinal fasciculus.
Outflow artery from the heart to the aortic arches.

Abductor muscle that develops from the primitive pectoral fin abductor.  It originates along the anterior skeletal flange of the pectoral girdle.  The abductor profundus bundles insert onto the fin ray base proximal processes of all fin rays.

Muscle located on ventral side of the head, linking the ventral hyoid arch to the dentary. Innervated by ramus mandibularis V and ramus hyoides VII.  Formed by the intermandibularis posterior and ventral interhyoideus.

comments:
Source: Winterbottom, R. 1973. A Descriptive Synonymy of the Striated Muscles of the Teleostei. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, Vol. 125 (1973), pp. 225-317.

In the zebrafish, as in most other teleosts, the interhyoideus becomes associated with the intermandibularis posterior, forming the protractor hyoideus. ZDB-PUB-080306-33.

definition.val: Collection of the visceromotor nuclei and their fiber tracts in the medulla oblongata.
Connective tissue partitions developing between the myotomes.

Brain structure which is caudally attached to the rostral medulla oblongata and extends into the tectal ventricle. The valvula cerebelli consists of a granular and a molecular layer along with aggregations of large Purkinje and eurydendroid cells and is uniquely present in ray-finned fishes. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.

Neural arch that extends along the dorso-lateral surface of the last preural centra and/or ural centra and the notochord (Arratia & Schultze, 1992). An uroneural develops as a modification of the neural arch of an ural centrum (Patterson, 1968). The series of uroneurals may include from 7 to 1 elements that are numbered from rostral to caudal. An uroneural is a paired membrane bone.
Diencephalic nucleus that is part of the synencephalon and the pretectum and is located periventricularly. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.

Cranial nerve that innervates the oculomotor system. The trochlear nerve is the only motor nerve to project dorsally and then cross the midline before exiting the neuroepithelium and re-orienting ventrally to project to the contralateral superior oblique extraocular muscle.
